Scanner stop mechanism
A new process scanner is started, but this time with the --stop-scan=scan _id
command line option.
The scan_id is the same as the scan task you want to stop.
This new scan process runs as root user, and therefore can send an interruption
signal to other process running as root user.
Run openvas --scan-stop=<scan_id>
Start the stop process
Every running scan task has Main KB in redis, where results and internal task's data is stored.
This new scan process goes through all redis kbs until the kb is found.
The identifier number of the KB is stored.
Search for the given scan_id in all redis KBs
The openvas PID of the scan task process .is stored in main kb found before, under the key "internal/ovas_pid".
Get the PID of the scan task to be stopped
With the right permissions and the PID of the main task process to be stopped, with send the SIGUSR1 signal not only to the main process, but to the process group.
Main scan process and all hosts process will receive the signal to start the stop process.
Stop the process
The global_stop_scan is a variable that is check many times in different parts of the code. The main process only set the variable during the interruption and does not perform
any other task. This is for avoiding deadlocks or segmentation faults. As a rule, an interruption must be as short as possible.

Set the global_stop_scan variable
After the Boreas thread has started, the scanner keep waiting for the first alive host.
If the scan is stopped, the code leaves the routine, and the scan finishes without
scanning code.
While waiting for the first alive host
While there are alive hosts, the main scan process keep looping and forking new
host processes in the mean there are available host process slots.
If during this routine the scan is stopped, no new host process will be forked
and main process enters into a new routine and waits for running hosts to finish.
Also, sends periodically the stop signal to the host processes, in case for some
reason they didn't cached it before.
While preparing and forking hosts
As well as hosts processes wait for plugin processes to finish, the main process
waits for all running hosts process.
The main scanner keeps a list of running host processes and goes through this list
where the host PID is stored, and check if the host process is still alive.
While the host are found dead, the main process cleans up the list until there are
no more host to check.
Waiting for hosts to finish
Each time that the global_stop_scan variable is checked, the scanner enters to a routine to cleanup the scan.
This routine check if it is a host process, or a main process via the PID process stored in the KB,
In the main process, it checks if the Boreas thread is still running and ensure it is closed gracefully.
Also, will sends the SIGUSR1 signal to all running host processes, again.
Better call scan_stop_cleanup()
Once all hosts finished, the main process ends the clean up for the main process and set the scan status as finihsed
Finish the scan
Check if the scan was stops
While the host process is looping in the plugins scheduler,it will check if the scan
was stopped to avoid storing results/status/scan progrees messages,
and to stop the plugin scheduler.
Just before launching the plugin, it checks again if the scan is stopped. Given the
case, it will set the plugin status as DONE without launch it.
It jumps out from the plugins scheduler loop and will wait for running plugins
to finish.
During the plugin launch
Each time that the global_stop_scan variable is checked, the scanner enters to a
routine to cleanup the scan. This routine check if it is a host process, or a main
process via the PID process stored in the KB.
For a host process, it will call pluginlaunch_stop(), to start the process of killing the
childs process running a plugin.
During the scan_stop_cleanup
When a plugin process is created, it becomes a process group leader. Also, a plugin process can fork() as well
to be run against different ports or vhosts for the same hosts.
The function to stop the running plugins goes through a list of process. This list stores, among other plugin
information, the PID. So, killing the Negative value of the PID (-PID) , it will send the signal to the whole
process group.
In the mean that plugins are killed, the host processes die as well.
